‚ĚĮ I have another device (HP Zbook g1a, a.k.a. wisp) which runs this nixos       
  flake. Every now and again the laptop crashes, and I can't figure out why.    
  Help me triage it. Here's what I know:                                        
                                                                                
  * the crashes happen on other OS installs too, leading me to suspect some     
  hardware settings                                                             
  * the crash is WAY more common -- almost predictable actually -- when booting 
   into a raw TTY with no desktop environment. Without a DE, the system will    
  crash in 5~15 minutes guaranteed. With a DE, the system can run days.         
  * I just rebooted from a crash now.                                           
                                                                                
  Help me triage that machine                                                   

‚óŹ Triage strategy: the TTY-crashes-fast / DE-stays-up pattern is a strong
  fingerprint. Things a desktop does that a bare TTY doesn't are basically: keep
   the GPU rendering, generate constant wake events, prevent deep idle. So the
  crash almost certainly happens when the system is allowed to enter a power
  state it can't reliably exit. On a brand-new platform like the ZBook G1a
  (Strix Halo / Ryzen AI Max), the prime suspects are deep C-states, amdgpu
  runtime PM, and PCIe ASPM ‚ÄĒ all consistent with "crashes on any OS, not just
  NixOS."

  Let me look at how wisp is configured in your flake before we go log-hunting.

  Read 2 files, listed 3 directories (ctrl+o to expand)

‚óŹ Wisp is on linuxPackages_latest with AMD microcode updates, a vanilla kvm-amd
  setup, and no power-management overrides. Nothing suspicious in the config ‚ÄĒ
  which is what we'd expect: hardware-level instability, no NixOS-specific
  tuning to blame.

  First thing to do ‚ÄĒ capture the previous boot's journal before it ages out.
  Run these on wisp (assuming you're SSH'd in or on the box now):

  # What kernel survived the crash, and what hardware?
  uname -r
  sudo dmidecode -s system-product-name
  sudo dmidecode -s bios-version

  # Persistent journals?
  sudo journalctl --list-boots | tail -5

  # The crashed boot is -1. Dump its tail to a file.
  sudo journalctl -b -1 -k -p warning..emerg --no-pager | tail -200
  sudo journalctl -b -1 -p err --no-pager | tail -100

  # Anything pstore left behind by the previous boot? (Often the only signal of 
  a hard hang.)
  ls -la /sys/fs/pstore/ /var/lib/systemd/pstore/ 2>/dev/null
  sudo dmesg | grep -iE 'pstore|mce|hardware error|ras'

  # Current runtime power state ‚ÄĒ to compare against what should change.
  cat /sys/devices/system/cpu/cpuidle/current_driver
  cat /sys/module/amd_pstate/parameters/* 2>/dev/null
  cat /sys/class/drm/card*/device/power_dpm_state 2>/dev/null

  Paste back the outputs and I'll read them. While you grab those, the working
  hypothesis ranking ‚ÄĒ best-fit-first for the TTY-vs-DE pattern:

  1. Deep CPU C-states. TTY lets the cores drop into the deepest idle (often
  C6/mwait); buggy silicon or firmware can hang there. Test: boot once with
  processor.max_cstate=1 idle=nomwait on the kernel cmdline. If wisp survives a
  30-min TTY session, this is it.
  2. amdgpu runtime power management / dpm. With no compositor, the iGPU
  power-gates aggressively. Strix-class AMD has a history of hangs on runpm.
  Test: amdgpu.runpm=0 amdgpu.dpm=0.
  3. PCIe ASPM. Aggressive link-state on NVMe/USB controllers when system is
  otherwise idle. Test: pcie_aspm=off.
  4. Firmware. Since it crashes across OSes, check fwupdmgr get-updates and the
  BIOS revision in HP's support page.

  Tell me what you're seeing and I'll narrow it.

