‚óŹ Two important signals to act on:

  1. You have crash dumps already. Most entries in /var/lib/systemd/pstore/ are
  size-6 stubs (empty), but several are larger ‚ÄĒ those almost certainly contain
  a saved kernel oops/panic from prior crashes. Read the most recent populated
  ones:

  ls -la /var/lib/systemd/pstore/1777451130/ /var/lib/systemd/pstore/1777451137/
  ls -la /var/lib/systemd/pstore/1776115206/ /var/lib/systemd/pstore/1776115207/
  sudo cat /var/lib/systemd/pstore/1777451130/* 2>/dev/null
  sudo cat /var/lib/systemd/pstore/1777451137/* 2>/dev/null
  # and for whichever else show size > 6:
  sudo find /var/lib/systemd/pstore -type f -exec ls -la {} \;

  Paste the contents of any non-empty file. That tells us whether it's a kernel
  oops (with backtrace), a watchdog timeout, or an MCE ‚ÄĒ each implies different
  fixes.

  2. Confirm the CPU + idle path. current_driver=acpi_idle and amd_pstate not
  loaded is suspicious on modern AMD. Run:

  grep -m1 'model name' /proc/cpuinfo
  cat /proc/cmdline
  ls /sys/devices/system/cpu/cpu0/cpuidle/
  for s in /sys/devices/system/cpu/cpu0/cpuidle/state*/name; do echo "$s: $(cat
  $s)"; done
  cat /sys/devices/system/cpu/cpu0/cpuidle/state*/disable
  cat /sys/devices/system/cpu/cpufreq/scaling_driver
  # replace dmidecode with the nix-shipped path:
  sudo /run/current-system/sw/bin/dmidecode -s system-product-name 2>/dev/null \
    || nix run nixpkgs#dmidecode -- -s system-product-name
  nix run nixpkgs#dmidecode -- -s bios-version
  nix run nixpkgs#dmidecode -- -s bios-release-date

  Side notes (not the main thread, but worth flagging):
  - _Q0A.WCCD AE_NOT_FOUND is an EC firmware bug ‚ÄĒ annoying noise, but unlikely
  to be your hang root cause. Worth a BIOS update regardless.
  - power_dpm_state=performance on the iGPU is unusual (default is balanced).
  Not the cause, just noting.

  After you paste the pstore contents and the CPU/idle output, I'll either point
   at a specific commit/issue or give you the kernel-cmdline experiment to
  bisect (cstate vs amdgpu vs ASPM) ‚ÄĒ one boot per variable.

