‚óŹ Verdict change: this isn't a power-management hang. It's kernel slab memory 
  corruption.

  All three Oopses crash at the same RIP: kmem_cache_free+0x406, dereferencing
  the same poisoned pointer 0x8e72ad0ab6cf3150 (in R12 across all three) from
  three different Chrome processes (PIDs 3535, 3762, 3477). That's a SLUB
  freelist corruption on skbuff_head_cache ‚ÄĒ and the same corrupted object keeps
   getting handed out, killing whoever touches it next. Hardware: HP ZBook Ultra
   G1a (Strix Halo), BIOS X89 01.03.02 2025-06-18. Brand-new platform.

  The crash happens ~52 seconds after the third s2idle resume in that boot, with
   amd_pmc: Last suspend didn't reach deepest state. So: a driver scribbles on 
  freed memory during s2idle resume; everything is fine until something free()s 
  an unix-socket skbuff that lands on the corrupted freelist entry.

  Why this matches the TTY-vs-DE pattern differently than I first thought: TTY
  does aggressive console-blank ‚Üí s2idle entries (consoleblank defaults to ~10
  min, but on AMD the EC + amd_pmc pull s2idle in fast). A DE is constantly
  waking the system, so fewer s2idle cycles per hour, so corruption accumulates
  slower. Chrome happens to be a heavy skbuff_head_cache consumer, so DE crashes
   manifest as this Oops; TTY likely crashes via the same root cause but in a
  different code path that hard-hangs without producing a pstore trace.

  Suspect drivers, all young on this platform, all in the loaded module list:
  - amdxdna (NPU)
  - amd_isp4 / pinctrl_amdisp / i2c_designware_amdisp (image signal processor)
  - amd_pmf (Platform Management Framework ‚ÄĒ known Strix resume bugs)
  - mt7925e (MediaTek WiFi¬†7)

  Action plan, by ROI:

  1. Cheapest test, run today. Disable console blanking + reduce s2idle exposure
   ‚ÄĒ directly attacks the trigger:
  boot.kernelParams = [ "consoleblank=0" ];
  services.logind.lidSwitch = "ignore";          # if you don't already
  services.logind.idleAction = "ignore";
  1. If wisp survives a 30-min TTY session where it normally dies in 5‚Äď15, the
  suspend/resume hypothesis is confirmed.
  2. Catch the next crash properly. Add to boot.kernelParams:
  "slub_debug=FZP"   # poison + free-after-free + writes detected at the 
  *write*, not the read
  "slab_nomerge"     # next oops will name the actual cache, not a merged alias
  "panic_on_warn"    # turn the first WARN_ON in the resume path into a clear 
  panic
  2. Worth the runtime cost ‚ÄĒ next crash should fingerprint the culprit driver.
  3. Driver bisect. Blacklist newest-and-least-essential first:
  boot.blacklistedKernelModules = [ "amdxdna" "amd_isp4" ];
  3. Then if still crashing: add amd_pmf. Then mt7925e (use ethernet/USB tether
  for that test).
  4. BIOS. X89 01.03.02 from 2025-06-18 is old by now. Run nix shell 
  nixpkgs#fwupd -c fwupdmgr refresh && fwupdmgr get-updates ‚ÄĒ HP ships Strix
  Halo updates through LVFS. Apply if any are listed.
  5. Kernel bracket. If 1‚Äď4 don't help, try pkgs.linuxPackages_cachyos or
  linuxPackages_xanmod_latest ‚ÄĒ they tend to carry Strix Halo and amdgpu fixes
  weeks ahead of mainline. Tells you whether 6.19.10 has a regression vs. a bug
  that's still upstream.

  Want me to write the boot.kernelParams + blacklist into
  hosts/wisp/configuration.nix for steps 1+2 so you can rebuild and start a TTY
  soak test? That's the fastest signal ‚ÄĒ if it doesn't crash in TTY by tonight,
  we have our answer; if it does, the next pstore tail will identify the cache
  and likely the driver.

